The 'pc_audio' is a port of the Linux HDA/SOF audio driver.

The driver exposes the mixer controls for all channels and devices in
its 'mixer' report that shares the format with the driver's configuration.
Using Sound Open Firmware (SOF) requires having the appropriate firmware
files as well as the Non-HDAudio-Link-Table (NHLT) in place.

At the moment the driver will always try to drive a compatible device
with SOF and only uses the regular HDA driver on systems where no DMIC
is available.


Testing
=======

The simplest way to test the driver is by executing the 'pc_audio.run'
run-script found in 'repos/pc/run':

! make KERNEL=nova BOARD=pc run/pc_audio

The run-script is configured in a way that all devices and mixer controls
are reported because it already contains the configuration profiles for a
variety of different systems but no profile is selected by default. Use
the 'profile' attribute in the 'config' node to choose the appriopriate
configuration profile for your system or follow the Configuration section
 In case there is none and create one yourself by inspecting the reports.

By default the run-script routes the microphone input to the Play session
and thus acts as a monitor.


Configuration
=============

The driver is configured by setting the appriopriate mixer controls and
audio devices. Since these can differ between varying systems the settings
are organized in profiles.

A profile contains a 'routing' node that specifies which devices should
be used for external/internal playback and external/internal recording.
It also contains the mixer controls that are managed by the driver for
switching between external/internal playback and recording automatically
(see Jack handling for more information).


Devices
~~~~~~~

In order to obtain a complete list of all devices encountered by the
driver enable

! config | report_devices: true

in the configuration node of the audio driver.

The most common devices are 'pcm0C0D0c' (recording) and 'pcmC0D0p'
(playback). Furthermore there is atleast on additionally recording
device in systems where SOF is used. Typically this is 'pcmC0D6c'
and presents the internal DMIC device. Older SOF devices call this
device 'DMIC' while newer ones 'DMIC Raw'.


Mixer controls
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The 'profile' node of the driver takes 'control' nodes as configuration inputs
which can be configured at runtime. There are three types of controls: integer,
boolean, and enumeration:

* Example for Integer:

! control Headphone Playback Volume | id: 0 | channel: 0 | type: int | value: 87 | min: 0 | max: 87
! control Headphone Playback Volume | id: 0 | channel: 1 | type: int | value: 87 | min: 0 | max: 87

This lets you configure the volume of the headphone playback for the left (0)
and right (1) channel. "min" and "max" indicate the supported range of the
"value" argument.

* Example for Boolean:

! control Headphone Playback Switch | id: 1 | channel: 0 | type: bool | value: true
! control Headphone Playback Switch | id: 1 | channel: 1 | type: bool | value: true

Boolean values are usually switches to turn on/off playback or recording. In
this example both playback channels of the headphone are enabled.

* Example for Enumeration:

! control Input Source  | id: 10 | type: enum | selected: 0
! + value Headset Mic   | id: 0
! + value Headphone Mic | id: 1
! -

Enumeration controls let's you select from 2 or more values (value-nodes).
Here the headset microphone is selected by the "selected" attribute.

The most common mixer controls can be found in the 'pc_audio.run' script.
In order to obtain a complete list of all controls enable

! config | report_mixer: true

in the configuration node of the audio driver.


Jack handling
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

When plugging, for example, a headset into the audio jack the driver will
automatically mute the speaker and the internal microphone (DMIC0) and unmute
the headphones and the headset microphone (default). If this behavior is not
desired, the following configuration options can be used:

! config | speaker_priority: external | mic_priority: internal


The example above configures the case when a headset is inserted: In this
example the headset's speaker will be enabled, the headset's microphone will be
disabled, and the internal microphone will be enabled. The priority implies
wnich device will be used in case internal and external are present (default is
external).

The microphone jack state changes additionally require that PCM devices
have to be switched because the headset microphone and the internal microphone
are two different PCM devices (pcmC0D0c, pcmC0D6c) - while the headphone and the
internal speaker share the same device (pcmC0D0p).


Firmware
========

Sound open firmware (SOF)
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The driver requires SOF image to be loaded during initialization.
Therefore, we provide a sof port.

! ./tool/port/prepare sof

will download the firmware. While the downloaded archive contains firmware for
all HDA devices, we only extract Tigerlake files here.

The files required for Tigerlake are:

! contrib/sof-<hash>/firmware/sof-tplg-v2.2.4/sof-hda-generic-2ch.tplg
! contrib/sof-<hash>/firmware/sof-v2.2.4/intel-signed/sof-tgl.ri

When using a run script you can either copy the files to '<build-dir>/bin' and
adjust the 'boot_modules' accordingly or import a depot package.

! import_from_depot [depot_user]/raw/sof_firmware


ACPI
~~~~

The drivers requires the NHLT (Non-HDAudio-Link) table in order to find the
internal microphone (DMIC). This table is provided by the platform driver
in case such a table was discovered during system bring-up.


Known issues
============

* When inserting the headset too slowly the microphone will generate noise
  instead of recording proper audio. This issue is not related to the driver but
  seems to be caused either by SOF or the hardware. The same can also be
  experienced on regular Linux distributions.
